  "prompt": "What universities for MS in CS should be considered with GRE - 317/340, CGPA - 9.15/10 and TOEFL - 102?",
  "response": "With a GRE score of **317/340**, a **CGPA of 9.15/10**, and a **TOEFL score of 102**, you have a strong profile for applying to top universities for an MS in Computer Science (CS). Your academic performance, combined with your GRE and TOEFL scores, positions you well for admission to competitive programs. Here\u2019s a list of universities you can consider based on your profile:\n\n---\n\n### **Ambitious/Top Tier Universities**\nThese are highly competitive programs, but your GPA and GRE score make you a competitive candidate:\n1. **University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign (UIUC)** - MSCS/MCS  \n2. **University of Texas at Austin (UT Austin)** - MS in CS  \n3. **University of California, San Diego (UCSD)** - MS in CS  \n4. **University of Wisconsin-Madison** - MS in CS  \n5. **University of Michigan, Ann Arbor** - MS in CSE  \n6. **University of Maryland, College Park (UMCP)** - MS in CS  \n7. **Purdue University** - MS in CS  \n\n---\n\n### **Moderate/Realistic Universities**\nThese universities are well-matched with your profile and offer strong CS programs:\n1. **University of Southern California (USC)** - MS in CS  \n2. **University of California, Irvine (UCI)** - MS in CS  \n3. **Texas A&M University, College Station** - MS in CS  \n4. **University of Florida (UF)** - MS in CS  \n5. **University of Minnesota, Twin Cities** - MS in CS  \n6. **North Carolina State University (NCSU)** - MS in CS  \n7. **Stony Brook University (SUNY)** - MS in CS  \n\n---\n\n### **Safe Universities**\nThese universities are good backups where your profile significantly exceeds the average requirements:\n1. **Arizona State University (ASU)** - MS in CS  \n2. **University of Colorado, Boulder** - MS in CS  \n3. **University of Utah** - MS in CS  \n4. **University of Illinois, Chicago (UIC)** - MS in CS  \n5. **George Mason University** - MS in CS  \n\n---\n\n### **Key Factors to Consider:**\n1. **Research Fit:** Look for universities with faculty and research areas aligned with your interests (e.g., AI, ML, Data Science, Cybersecurity, etc.).\n2. **Location and Cost:** Consider tuition fees, cost of living, and job opportunities in the area.\n3. **GRE Score Consideration:** While your GRE score is solid, some top-tier universities may focus more on GPA and research experience. If possible, highlight your strengths in your SOP and LORs.\n4. **TOEFL Score:** Your TOEFL score meets or exceeds the requirements of most universities, so this is a strong point in your application.\n\n---\n\n### **Next Steps:**\n- Shortlist 6\u20138 universities (2\u20133 ambitious, 2\u20133 moderate, and 1\u20132 safe).\n- Focus on crafting a strong **Statement of Purpose (SOP)** and securing strong **Letters of Recommendation (LORs)**.\n- Highlight any relevant research, internships, or projects in your application.\n\nGood luck with your applications! Let me know if you need help with SOPs or university selection.",
